 of psychological intervention studies.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G022593/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Traditional statistical techniques in the social sciences fail to account for hierarchical or 'nested' structures commonly found in data from applied settings. A classic example is that of children who may be considered 'nested' within classes, schools, education authorities, and regions or countries. Each one of these groupings may influence variables of interest, and without taking account of this hierarchical structure researchers may draw erroneous conclusions. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>This 'multilevel' approach is equally well suited to analysing data from trials of psychotherapeutic interventions (an area of interest), and when pooling data or estimates of effect size from multiple studies (mega, or meta-analysis). &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The purpose of this postdoctoral fellowship is to enable Dr Whalley to acquire and disseminate expertise of recent methological developments in this area. The aim is to contribute to the ESRC's programme to build capacity in advanced quantitative techniques, and Dr Whalley will be mentored by leading researchers at the Centre for Multilevel Modelling, one of ESRC's funded 'nodes' for research methods. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>In addition to applying multilevel techniques to data collected during his PhD, Dr Whalley will collaborate with researchers in the UK and USA to apply these techniques to existing data-sets which evaluate the effectiveness of different psychotherapeutic techniques. &lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2010-01-04</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>50663</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:collaborationOutput><gtr:collaboratingOrganisation>University of Southampton</gtr:collaboratingOrganisation><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:department>School of Health Sciences</gtr:department><gtr:description>Mechanisms and outcomes in dialectical behaviour therapy</gtr:description><gtr:id>4BF43A52-0710-4769-A9D9-818260217C4D</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The trial is now underway and has recruited &amp;gt;150 patients. We are on track to complete recruitment in 2016.
